### Dartz Error Handling
- Use `Either<Failure, T>` for error control without throwing across layers
- `Left` represents failure; `Right` represents success
- Create a base `Failure` class and extend it for specific error types
- Map data-layer exceptions to domain `Failure` types inside repositories
- Use `fold()` to handle success and failure in one place
- Never use `async`/`await` inside `fold()` callbacks — extract values first, then run async work outside
- Prefer this pattern over `DataSuccess` / `DataFailed` (do not use those types)

```dart
import 'package:dartz/dartz.dart';
import 'package:equatable/equatable.dart';

/// Base failure for domain/presentation error mapping.
/// Example: return Left(ServerFailure('Unable to fetch rates'));
abstract class Failure extends Equatable {
  final String message;

  const Failure(this.message);

  @override
  List<Object> get props => [message];
}

class ServerFailure extends Failure {
  const ServerFailure([super.message = 'Server error occurred']);
}

class CacheFailure extends Failure {
  const CacheFailure([super.message = 'Cache error occurred']);
}

class NetworkFailure extends Failure {
  const NetworkFailure([super.message = 'Network error occurred']);
}

class ValidationFailure extends Failure {
  const ValidationFailure([super.message = 'Validation failed']);
}

/// Helpers for Either<Failure, T> in UI and chaining.
extension EitherExtensions<L, R> on Either<L, R> {
  R getRight() => (this as Right<L, R>).value;

  L getLeft() => (this as Left<L, R>).value;

  T when<T>({
    required T Function(L failure) failure,
    required T Function(R data) success,
  }) {
    return fold(failure, success);
  }

  Either<L, T> flatMap<T>(Either<L, T> Function(R r) f) {
    return fold((l) => Left(l), (r) => f(r));
  }
}
```
